<main id="main">
  <h1 id="title">Maya Angelou</h1>
  <h2>Award-winning author and poet</h2>
  <figure id="img-div">
    <img
      id="image"
      src="https://kentakepage.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Maya-Angelou.jpg" alt="Maya Angelou portrait.>"class="responsive"</p>
 
   <p> <figcaption id="img-caption">
     American poet, author, singer, dancer and civil rights activist.</p>
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
  <body>
  <section id="tribute-info">
    
    <div id="tribute-info">
      <p>Angelou was born on April 4, 1928, in St. Louis, Missouri. Maya and her older brother, lived with their grandmother Anne Henderson, in Stamps, Arkansas, after their parents divorced. 
  While visiting her mother Angelou was sexually assaulted by her mothers boyfriend around the age of 7. Maya's uncles murdered the boyfriend after Maya informed family of the sexual assault. Believing her words caused his murder young Maya Angelou refused to speak for 5 years. Bertha Flowers was a local school teacher who cleverly used Maya's love of books to help her reclaim her voice. Maya's first autobiographical book I Know Why the Cage Bird Sings, included the rape and racism she experienced from the 3 to 16 yrs of age.</p>   
      </section>
  </div>
    <div id="content">
       <div class="column-1">
      <h3>1940</h3>
      <p>Angelou moves to San francisco with her mother and brother where she learns to dance. She gives birth to a son at age 16. She moved to San Diego to financially support her child she worked as a nightclub waitress, prostitute, and danced in a strip club. She was later discovered by a theatre group while working at the strip club.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
       <div class="column-1">
      <h3>1954</h3>
     <p> She auditioned for an international tour of Porgy and Bess and won a role. From 1954 to ’55, she toured 22 countries.<a target=_"blank" href="https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=125457527"</a>Maya Angelou interview on NPR discussing her role in Porgy and Bess.
</a></p> 
    </div>
   <div class="content">
     <div class="column-1">
      <h3>1969</h3>
      <p>I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings is published. When Maya returned to the U.S., she began publishing her multivolume autobiography, starting with I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings. Four more volumes appeared during thenext two decades, as well as several books of poetry.<a target=_"blank" href="https://youtu.be/QC_scsKVEHA"</a> Maya Angelou discusses I Know Why the Cage Birds Sings with Oprah Winfrey.
</a></p>
    </div>
  <div class="content">
       <div class="column-2">
      <h3>1981</h3>
      <p>Angelou was appointed Professor of American Studies at Wake Forest University in Winston-Salem.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
       <div class="column-2">
      <h3>1993</h3>
      <p>Maya Angelou writes On the Pulse of the Morning and reads the poem at President Clinton’s inauguration.<a target=_"blank" href="https://youtu.be/59xGmHzxtZ4"</a>Maya Angelou reciting her poem "On the Pulse of Morning" at the 1993 Presidential Inaugural.</a></p>
    </div>
  <div class="content">
       <div class="column-2">
      <h3>2014</h3>
     <p> Maya Angelou died on May 28, 2014, in North Carolina. She was 86 years old. <a target=_"blank" href="https://youtu.be/C2s-1050fWE"</a>Oprah Winfrey delivers eulogy at the funeral service for Dr. Maya Angelou.</a></p>
    </div>
